defaultals are essential for economic 
defaultdevelopment. 
defaultFor its small size Britain is 
defaultrelatively
default well endowed with mineral resources and their e
defaultxtraction and use have played an important part in the historic development of the UK economy. The UK continues to have an economically 
defaultsignificant
default minerals industry, with oil and gas, and construction and in
defaultdustrial minerals being important sectors. Although much diminished, coal still makes an important contribution to our energy mix. The contribution that these minerals make 
defaultto
default the national economy 
defaultmay
default be considered 
defaultin two
default ways. First there is the primary c
defaultontribution they make in terms of added value and employment associated with 
defaulttheir
default extraction and processing; and then there is the secondary 
defaultcontribution they
default make to the competitiveness of the
default downstream
default industries they support. Nevertheless, the UK 
defaultalso 
defaulthas 
defaultsubstantial
default and increasing 
defaultforeign
default dependence for minera
defaultl supplies. This not only places
default 
defaultincreasing 
defaultdemands
default on the environments of ou
defaultr trading partners
default but potentially makes us more vulnerable to supply disruptions 
defaultas global demand for minerals gr
defaultowths driven by expanding populations and rising incomes. There will be a continuing demand for the products of the UK’s extractive industries for the foreseeable future.
